A modified version of Anchovie's PT2399 Noise Ensemble circuit 
(https://www.diystompboxes.com/smfforum/index.php?topic=87493.0), 
turned into a touch-based instrument that can also process external sounds.
Schematics of the original stripboard layout, as well as various modifications
of the circuit, can be found online. The original circuit is preserved here,
but with the addition of various touch points along the copper traces — the original
design (displayed at the Here and Now exhibition) has seven touch points, but 
further experimentation has yielded a greater number.

As with the other instruments in the Screecher family, the Soprano Screecher emits
sounds when its brass buttons are touched by human skin. Pressing different
combinations of buttons with varying amounts of pressure is how different sounds
are produced. The two potentiometers (knobs) adjust the volume and delay time of
whichever sounds are processed through the input. 
